== 3. Basics of Molecular Orbital Diagrams

=== 3.1 Simplest MO Diagram

A minimal example where one molecular orbital is formed from two atomic orbitals.

#mo(
  width: 12,
  height: 8,
  atom1: ((energy: -5, electrons: 1),),
  molecule: ((energy: -8, electrons: 2),),
  atom2: ((energy: -5, electrons: 1),),
)

=== 3.2 Bonding and Antibonding Orbitals

Display both bonding and antibonding orbitals.

#mo(
  width: 12,
  height: 8,
  atom1: ((energy: -5, electrons: 1),),
  molecule: (
    (energy: -8, electrons: 2),
    (energy: -2, electrons: 0),
  ),
  atom2: ((energy: -5, electrons: 1),),
)

=== 3.3 Connections Between Orbitals

Use labels to show correspondence between atomic and molecular orbitals.

#mo(
  width: 12,
  height: 8,
  atom1: ((energy: -5, electrons: 1, label: 1),),
  molecule: (
    (energy: -8, electrons: 2, label: 2),
    (energy: -2, electrons: 0, label: 3),
  ),
  atom2: ((energy: -5, electrons: 1, label: 4),),
  (1, 2), (1, 3), (4, 2), (4, 3)
)

=== 3.4 With Captions

Add captions to orbitals.

#mo(
  width: 12,
  height: 8,
  atom1: ((energy: -5, electrons: 1, label: 1, caption: "1s"),),
  molecule: (
    (energy: -8, electrons: 2, label: 2, caption: [$sigma$]),
    (energy: -2, electrons: 0, label: 3, caption: [$sigma^*$]),
  ),
  atom2: ((energy: -5, electrons: 1, label: 4, caption: "1s"),),
  (1, 2), (1, 3), (4, 2), (4, 3)
)

=== 3.5 Displaying Atomic and Molecular Names

Display names for left atom, central molecule, and right atom with the `names` parameter.

#mo(
  width: 12,
  height: 8,
  names: ("H", $"H"_2$, "H"),
  atom1: ((energy: -5, electrons: 1, label: 1, caption: "1s"),),
  molecule: (
    (energy: -8, electrons: 2, label: 2, caption: [$sigma$]),
    (energy: -2, electrons: 0, label: 3, caption: [$sigma^*$]),
  ),
  atom2: ((energy: -5, electrons: 1, label: 4, caption: "1s"),),
  (1, 2), (1, 3), (4, 2), (4, 3)
)

